  <p>
    Melanocortin pharmacology has moved from curiosity to clinic. This section
    will cover approved agents and the investigational frontier, each entry
    carrying a last-reviewed date because pipeline information dates quickly.
  </p>
  <h2>Approved</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Setmelanotide</strong> — an MC4R agonist for rare genetic obesity.</li>
    <li><strong>Afamelanotide</strong> — an α-MSH analogue used in erythropoietic protoporphyria.</li>
    <li><strong>Bremelanotide</strong> — a melanocortin agonist for hypoactive sexual desire disorder.</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>The frontier</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Next-generation MC4R agonists and biased ligands aimed at efficacy without blood-pressure liabilities.</li>
    <li>MC1R and MC3R agonists explored for anti-inflammatory and tissue-protective effects.</li>
    <li>Peptide and small-molecule approaches across dermatology, metabolism, and immunology.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Each drug will get a cited entry. Until then, this is an outline of where the
    section is headed — not clinical guidance.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
